alled Stratton or Stretton, almost all named with Old English <i>strǣt</i> ‘paved road, Roman road’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’. Stratton in Cornwall, which may also be a partial source of the surname, probably has as its first element Cornish <i>stras</i> ‘valley’.","English: variant of <b>Sturton</b>, a habitational name from Sturton le Steeple (Nottinghamshire), Great Sturton (Lincolnshire), Sturton by Stow (Lincolnshire), or possibly Sturton (Northumberland), all of which placenames share the same etymology and early spellings as 1 above.","Scottish: habitational name from Straiton (Ayrshire), Straiton in Liberton (Midlothian), or South Straiton in Logie (Fife), all named with Old English <i>strǣt</i> ‘street, Roman road’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."],"variants":[{"name":"Stretton","meanings":["English (Leicestershire): variant of   Stratton   1."]},{"name":"Strutton","meanings":["English (Middlesex): variant of   Stratton  ."]},{"name":"Straiton","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Straiton (Ayrshire), Straiton in Liberton (Midlothian), or South Straiton in Logie (Fife), all named with Old English <i>strǣt</i> ‘paved road, street’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. Compare   Stratton  ."]}]},{"name":"Mathew","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Matthew ."],"variants":[{"name":"Matthew","meanings":["form of the name of the Christian evangelist, author of the first gospel in the New Testament. His name is a form of the Hebrew name <i>Mattathia</i>, meaning ‘gift of God’, which is fairly common in the Old Testament, being rendered in the Authorized Version in a number of different forms: <i>Mattan(i)ah</i>, <i>Mattatha(h)</i>, <i>Mattithiah</i>, <i>Mattathias</i>, and so on. In the Authorized Version, the evangelist is regularly referred to as <i>Matthew</i>, while the apostle chosen to replace Judas Iscariot is distinguished as   Matthias .  A related name from the same Hebrew roots, but reversed, is   Jonathan .  Throughout the English-speaking world <i>Matthew</i> has been particularly popular since the 1970s."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705185,"age":7,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705187,"age":116,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Mathew Stratton was born in 1099, in Cothelstone, Somerset, England. He married Mrs Mathew Stratton in 1124, in Cothelstone, Somerset, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"1099–":"1099–Surnud","1104–Female":"1104–Surnud","1129–Female":"1129–Surnud","1099–Male":"1099–Surnud","1129":"1129","1106":"1106","1215":"1215","1104":"1104","about 1129":"umbes 1129","1124":"1124","1099":"1099","Cothelstone, Somerset, England":"Cothelstone, Somerset, England","England":"England"},"fi":{"1099–":"1099–Kuollut","1104–Female":"1104–Kuollut","1129–Female":"1129–Kuollut","1099–Male":"1099–Kuollut","1129":"1129","1106":"1106","1215":"1215","1104":"1104","about 1129":"noin 1129","1124":"1124","1099":"1099","Cothelstone, Somerset, England":"Cothelstone, Somerset, England","England":"England"},"fr":{"1099–":"1099–Décédé","1104–Female":"1104–Décédée","1129–Female":"1129–Décédée","1099–Male":"1099–Décé